{"headline": "Signs of Affection, or Not, at the Old Ballgame", "body": "\nRules of grammar need not be obeyed. Sloppy penmanship and cornpone humor are welcome. The bigger the better.         \n\nThese are the ground rules of baseball signs, held aloft by fans at games and parades over the years to send a message to players, other fans, TV audiences or anyone else who will look their way. Sometimes they are twists on popular phrases. Sometimes they are Bible verses. Always they are G-rated, lest security confiscate them.         \n\nA series of pictures from the Times photography archives shows baseball signs through the ages, from a Brooklyn parade for the Dodgers in 1941 to a homecoming for the Royals after their loss in the 1976 A.LC.S.         \n\nWe also want to hear from you. What\u2019s the best sign you have seen at a sporting event? Have you ever made one? Tell us your story in the comments.        ", "url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2013/10/16/sports/baseball/signs-of-affection-or-not-at-the-old-ballgame.html", "date": "2013-10-15", "description": "In a series of pictures from the Times photography archives we look at baseball signs through the years."}